ocr.sentence: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur.
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

ocr.line: νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A.
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

ocr.line: tur. Rectius Schol. Rom. τοῖς ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο,
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. ocr.line: λήν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph.
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

Leocr. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thucydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum, nec dubita- tione caruit εἰ θέλοιμεν Vl. 34, ⟨. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 154. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Λείας. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Hesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur τοῖς κυσί, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur ; idemque sensisse videtur qui v. 232. adscripsit : οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjecturam sequun- tur. Rectius Schol. Rom. τοῖς ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, ἵνα μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων τὸ σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. Δ. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra scripto νέμει. Illud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p. 306. e glossa εἰς αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. Xl. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν αἰτίαν. V. 29. Καί μοί τις ὀπτήρ - εἰςιδών - haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Ὀπτήρ, totum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. l. affert. ED. PR. V. 30 Πηδῶντα πεδία. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret ; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην Iesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λήν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. c. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾶσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος 0ed. C. 1686. τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν βεβώς Aesch, Eum. 76.

Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

ocr.line: I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾶσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

ocr.region: the fiery man. Essay on L. §9. P. 12, 2. If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occur- ring in Hesychius in the right alpha- betical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound has sometimes little significance (see esp. infr. 954, κελαι- νῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here, and has the preponderance of MS. authority in its favour. 222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] ‘That can neither be avoided nor endared.’ 225. μεγάλων] ‘Terrible.’ The mari- ners, in their feebleness (supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a commenut on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ pyasus) ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in geneial. ἀέξει] Not "exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

prediction.region: The first clause is of the same origin as the other clauses in the whole passage, but, in the last clause, the sense is quite different. It is a criticism. In all these clauses, there is the same kind of expression as in the words of the suprasegment (supr. 169, & 170). There the words μεγάλα φάτις are employed in the sense of ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad,’ while they are here used in the sense of ‘that which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’ 228. σὺ] Not σώσω (supra, vi. 14). In the suprasegment the same sense is employed. It is quite impossible for σὺ to denote the idea of a person. Supr. 160. 230. μὴ] ‘Not that he shall do so.’ In the suprasegment, μὴ and μῶν are used interchangeably in the sense of ‘not that he shall do so, but that he shall do otherwise.’ Here, μὴ is used in the sense of ‘not,’ and the sense is therefore different. 231. ἄκοντος] This is the same word as in infr. 241 (infr. 242 is equivalent to the Greek καὶ). The form ἄκοντος is preferred over καὶ in that it is used more generally. As the passage is concerned with the opinion of the enemy, the word ἐνανοία is the better, because in the suprasegment it is used only in the sense of ‘to act in the opposite way,’ as in infr. 246. 232. τιμήν] ‘Terror.’ ὑστέρωσιν] ‘To be terrified.’ τριήν] ‘Terrible.

prediction.region: The first clause is of the same origin as the other clauses in the whole passage, but, in the last clause, the sense is quite different. It is a criticism. The form ἄκοντος is preferred over καὶ in that it is used more generally. As the passage is concerned with the opinion of the enemy, the word ἐνανοία is the better, because in the suprasegment it is used only in the sense of ‘to act in the opposite way,’ as in infr. 246. 232. τιμήν] ‘Terror.’ ὑστέρωσιν] ‘To be terrified.’ τριήν] ‘Terrible.

prediction.region: away the bones.’ The expression is of great importance, but it will not answer the question. I cannot understand its meaning. 237. νεοθυμισμῶν] A term common to the old and new testaments, usually applied to those who refused to pay orally; cf. Prov. 8, 21, 21. For ἱππόνμαν, see under Supr. 9. p. 8. The term, though used in both senses, is more frequently applied to the Roman soldiers. The passage is also used in a similar sense (Tract. 286; Pyrrh. 7). The expression πλευροκοπῶν δίχ’ ἀνερρήγνυ is well known to the students of classical literature. The general meaning of the term seems to be the same in both cases. κομὸν is a colloquial term for ‘of any sort,’ and, as in Tr. 286, μὲν ἐκ μᾶλλον δοί. 238. εἶναι μαθητὴν μετερίκυ] ‘I was of opinion that it was well.’ There are three forms for ἐνειπεῖν. First, ἐνεἶναι, ἐνεἰπεῖν, ‘I agree with’ or ‘I like’; cf. Cato’s reply (Tac. 4, 32, 12); the second is ἐνεὺπεῖν, ‘I wish’; cf. P. Varr. 1, 5, 17. The third ἐνεῖπεῖν, ‘I should like’ is probably the earliest form, and is perhaps derived from ἐνίπιπεῖν, ‘I wish,’ or from ἐνίπεῖν, ‘I will,’ from which the latter is the derivative. A parallelism of this kind would explain ἐνε

In the first half of the poem, the sense of this phrase, so widely diffused among Greeks, is, ‘to be crushed, to have no hope;’ but in the end of the work, it signifies, ‘to die, to perish.’ The word τύχη is used by Plato (Met. 427 D.2. 4) to denote, according to the expression of Cicero (De Rep. 1. 26), a ‘barren, wasteful, and unproductive space,’ which is a common and significant synonym for an empty place. The word is evidently the same as τύχην, a ‘barren’ space; and in Euripides, the sense is almost precisely the same as that of Ptol. The word τύχη occurs frequently in the Greek tragedians, as well as in the epics and histories. It is applied to many spaces, such as the interior of the house, a temple, or the garden. We shall here translate it for ‘sacrifice,’ or ‘sacrificial space,’ although the meaning is quite different. The word is evidently the same as τύχην, a ‘barren’ space; and in Euripides, the sense is almost precisely the same as that of Ptol. The word τύχη occurs frequently in the Greek tragedians, as well as in the epics and histories. It is applied to many spaces, such as the interior of the house, a temple, or the garden. We shall here translate it for ‘sacrifice,’ or ‘sacrificial space,’ although the meaning is quite different. prediction.region: over you, and Zeus the king, and Zeus of the sky, and the sun and the moon, and the seven heavenly nymphs, and the seven goddesses of the earth, and the deity who made you, and the Goddess who made you, you are a happy man in my house and in all my courts. I have made you happy, and you will, like the rest, keep up your happiness. I, too, will keep up the happiness of all my people and my servants.” The words are delivered by her father; but Oenotheos, in order to make his wife more happy, makes an additional speech. It is a very good specimen of Greek poetry; and the very language, the subject, and the diction are admirable. The words of Oenotheos (cp. infra, l. 49, p. 74, ad l. 53) are not very happy, nor did he make his wife happy. This is not true for the women, who can be unhappy on account of their husbands. For the subject in ἐφεστίου Ads | εὐνῆς τε τῆς σῆς is that which is common to both women and men. There is no such thing as unmarryable persons; nor is it, I believe, true for the women that the words ἅν εἰπεκίους ἔδουσιν ἀλλ’ ἀναδίχοντες ἔδουσιν ἀγνωμοὶ (O. groundtruth.region: 715. ἐξ ἀέλπτων] ‘When we had despaired.’ Cp. supr. 648. 716. μετανεγνώσθη] ‘Has been con- verted.’ Ajax, supr. 651, attributed the change in himself to the persuasion of Tecmessa. 717. θυμῶν] This reading, which occurs in some MSS., is nearer to θυμόν, the reading of L, than the conj. θυμοῦ τʼ, which has been commonly adopted. For the poetical plural, ‘outbursts of wrath,’ cp. Trach. 882, τίνες νόσοι; and see Essay on L. § 20. p. 30. The plural of θυμός occurs in Plat. Phil. 40 E: Legg. 11. 934 A, ὁ δὲ ..ἐν φόβοις δειλίας, ἤ τισιν ἐπιθυμίαις ἢ φθόνοις ἢ θυμοῖς δυ- σιάτοις γιγνόμενος. (νεικεων.) 719 foll. The proscenium has been vacant during the preceding ode. A single figure is now seen approaching from the opposite direction to that in which Ajax went forth. The man proves to be Teucer’s forerunner. The effect of the following scene is twofold. On the one hand, the Chorus and Tecmessa are roused from their security, and go anxiously in search of
prediction.line: the word θυμός, in which we may discern a certain relation between the matter
prediction.region: Ajax. On the other hand, it reminds the people that the victor has escaped. The following scene shows the man approaching the entrance to the Theatre. On either side of him stands the whole city, shouting to his companions that he is their guide. The people have now become aware of Ajax’s flight, and look up in wonder. 720. ἀντὸς] A synonymous reading in the same context is ἀνθρώπῳ. Cf. supra, p. 302, n. 3. The reading of L. ἀντὸς is nearer to the sense of the original than is that of L., which seems to be more natural. For the same reason the words αἱ διδάκουσι may also be read διδάκουσιν. 721. ἐν τῶν] The reading ἐν τοῖς seems to be more natural, and therefore adopted. The expression τῶν τῶν is also used in Athen. v. 1391: ἀσῶν τῶν τῶν ἔργων, ὠφι- γώτων. (πολλοῖς.) The sentence is in the form ἐπὶ τοῖς τῶν τῶν ἔργων, ὠφιγ- ϑώτων, ὡς ἐπὶ τοῖς τῶν τῶν ἔργων, ὠφιγ- ϑώτων. Cf. also supra, p. 305. This reading

prediction.region: speaks of a time of darkness and confusion, in which the good and the bad come together, the old and the young meet and die; but, in the midst of it all, the old gods bring forth a king. The passage is the first to speak of the god of war as the great beneficent, and he is represented as an incarnate hero, the Son of Zeus, who comes to rescue the world from the tyranny of the powers of darkness. His advent has been anticipated by the sun; the new day has come, and he stands forth, the glorious figure of the divine nature: and, when the messenger reaches Tecmessa, the poet’s mind is still at rest. When the messenger returns with his tidings, Tecmessa’s mind is no longer at rest, for there are now no words of hope and hope: the new day, which she has just seen, is a day of darkness, which will bring her death. Thus the messenger brings back, with his tidings of destruction, to Tecmessa and the world, the same darkness that she has already seen. Her own death is not mentioned; that is, it would have been too long to dwell on it here, and the writer had no wish to enlarge on that theme. But a little further on he makes her think of the time of ignorance, the time of ignorance of death; the old man’s death in the past, the young man’s death in the present; that is, the time of darkness which now presents itself. In that time she has known and seen death: and this experience will bring her to think, when she has seen and known all that is, that the good god who is incarnate in the heroic deity, is the true god, the true creator and sustainer of the world, and she is but the mortal who is created in his image. To see this truth, to be sure, would be death

prediction.region: speaks of a time of darkness and confusion, in which the good and the bad come together, the old and the young meet and die; but, in the midst of it all, the old gods bring forth a king. The passage is the first to speak of the god of war as the great beneficent, and he is represented as an incarnate hero, the Son of Zeus, who comes to rescue the world from the tyranny of the powers of darkness. His advent has been anticipated by the sun; the new day has come, and he stands forth, the glorious figure of the divine nature: and, when the messenger reaches Tecmessa, the poet’s mind is still at rest. When the messenger returns with his tidings, Tecmessa’s mind is no longer at rest, for there are now no words of hope and hope: the new day, which she has just seen, is a day of darkness, which will bring her death. Thus the messenger brings back, with his tidings of destruction, to Tecmessa and the world, the same darkness that she has already seen. Her own death is not mentioned; that is, it would have been too long to dwell on it here, and the writer had no wish to enlarge on that theme. But a little further on he makes her think of the time of ignorance, the time of ignorance of death; the old man’s death in the past, the young man’s death in the present; that is, the time of darkness which now presents itself. In that time she has known and seen death: and this experience will bring her to think, when she has seen and known all that is, that the good god who is incarnate in the heroic deity, is the true god, the true creator and sustainer of the world, and she is but the mortal who is created in his image. To see this truth, to be sure, would be death

prediction.region: speaks of a time of darkness and confusion, in which the good and the bad come together, the old and the young meet and die; but, in the midst of it all, the old gods bring forth a king. The passage is the first to speak of the god of war as the great beneficent, and he is represented as an incarnate hero, the Son of Zeus, who comes to rescue the world from the tyranny of the powers of darkness. His advent has been anticipated by the sun; the new day has come, and he stands forth, the glorious figure of the divine nature: and, when the messenger reaches Tecmessa, the poet’s mind is still at rest. When the messenger returns with his tidings, Tecmessa’s mind is no longer at rest, for there are now no words of hope and hope: the new day, which she has just seen, is a day of darkness, which will bring her death. Thus the messenger brings back, with his tidings of destruction, to Tecmessa and the world, the same darkness that she has already seen. Her own death is not mentioned; that is, it would have been too long to dwell on it here, and the writer had no wish to enlarge on that theme. But a little further on he makes her think of the time of ignorance, the time of ignorance of death; the old man’s death in the past, the young man’s death in the present; that is, the time of darkness which now presents itself. In that time she has known and seen death: and this experience will bring her to think, when she has seen and known all that is, that the good god who is incarnate in the heroic deity, is the true god, the true creator and sustainer of the world, and she is but the mortal who is created in his image. To see this truth, to be sure, would be death

Tacitus calls this sort of address an ἐνομίσκη, which, however, he does not distinguish between ἐνομίσκη Ἀντωνικίαι and ἐνομίσκη Βοῦλικι (1. 3. 12).—In these last cases we may follow the more common usage in other instances.
In the present passage the οὐρανής was addressed to the inhabitants of the camp, and not to the choregus, as we find in the other two instances in the Iliad. In the first part, it was addressed to a select number of persons, but in the second part it was addressed to all. The other forms, however, of ἐνομίσκη, which Tacitus calls the οὐρανής Ἀντωνικίαι, were only addressed to the choregus. In this sense they would probably be regarded as ἐνομίσκη Ηγείωνι, i. e. addressed to the choreutai and Tecmessa. The οὐρανής ἐνομίσκη Βοῦλικι, on the other hand, was addressed to the choreutai, Tecmessa, and to the whole chorus.

Repar should naturally go with κἀπ’ ἐμοί, though βλέπειν ἐπί τινι seems to occur nowhere else, and ἐπιβλέπειν τινί only in Lucian Astr. 20 καὶ σφίσι γνομένοισι τῷ μὲν ἡ Ἀφροδίτη τῷ δὲ ὁ Ζεὺς... ἐπέβλεψαν (‘loocked with favour’). The alternative is to take ἐπ’ uol as= ‘in my case,’ and βλέψας as epexegetic ; but this is certainly harsh. 846 f. διοίγω: cp. O. T. 1287 διοί- γειν kA6pa, and ib. 1295.—mpdyn, deeds: cp. 21. Pe ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The word πράγη in 247, and the language of vv. 351 ff., show that the carnage was represented. The other plays in which Sophocles has used the eccyclema are the Antigone (1294, where see n.), and the Electra (1464 f., n.). The ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The other plays in which Sophocles has used the eccyclema are the Antigone (1294, where see n.), and the Electra (1464 f., n.). Ajax, siting among his victims, and meditating his own destruction, was the subject of a famous picture by Timomachus of Byzantium. Philostratus ( Vit. ocr.region: κἀπ’ dpol: for this modest καί, cp. Ph. 192 εἴπερ κἀγώ τι φρονῶ, and n. on Ant. 719. Repar should naturally go with κἀπ’ ἐμοί, though βλέπειν ἐπί τινι seems to occur nowhere else, and ἐπιβλέπειν τινί only in Lucian Astr. 20 καὶ σφίσι γνομένοισι τῷ μὲν ἡ Ἀφροδίτη τῷ δὲ ὁ Ζεὺς... ἐπέβλεψαν (‘loocked with favour’). The alternative is to take ἐπ’ uol as= ‘in my case,’ and βλέψας as epexegetic ; but this is certainly harsh. 846 f. διοίγω: cp. O. T. 1287 διοί- γειν kA6pa, and ib. 1295.—mpdyn, deeds: cp. 21. Pe ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The word πράγη in 247, and the language of vv. 351 ff., show that the carnage was represented. The other plays in which Sophocles has used the eccyclema are the Antigone (1294, where see n.), and the Electra (1464 f., n.). Ajax, sitting among his victims, and meditating his own destruction, was the subject of a famous picture by Timomachus of Byzantium. Philostratus ( Vit. Apoll. 2. 22 § 5) thus describes it: rov Alavra. τὸν Τιμομάχου. . dwexrovbra τἀν τῇ Τροίᾳ βουκόλια καθῆσθαι ἀπειρηκότα [cp. ν. 325 ἤσυχος θακεῖ], βουλὴν ποιούμενον καὶ

ocr.sentence: 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere.
ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

Ν. 4. 36, and Callim. Epigr. 13 (καί σφιν ἀνιηρὸν μὲν ἐρεῖς ἔπος, ἔμπα δὲ λέξον). A Doric form ἔμπάν is used by Pind. Ρ. 5. 51. In 122 and 1338 as in Ant. 845, we have ἔμπας. ocr.region: möchte. εὔρινος (Nebenform zu εὔρις) bei βάσις worin τὸ edowor ſich zu erkennen gibt, wie oft Epitheta von der Perſon auf die Handlung übertragen werden. Die lakoniſchen Hunde, welche bei der Jagd im Taygetos dienten, werden ſchon von Pindar Fragm. 83 als treffliche Spürhunde ge- rühmt. 10. Das Epitheton ξιφοκτόνους vertritt die Stelle von aluarı (στάζων). 13. örov.. μάθῃς d. 1. ſage mir, was du erfahren willſt; ich kann dir Auskunft geben. 14. Bei Sophokles kommt nur die Form 496"a vor, bei Äſchylo8 auch die alte, feierliche Form Ἀθηναία. 15. ds iſt cauſal. Odyſſeus gibt an, warum er Athena ſofort erkannt habe. εὐμαθές iſt be- tont als Gegenſaß zu ἄποπτος (wenn ich dich auch nicht deutlich ſehe, er- kenne ich doch deutlich deine Stimme“). — ἐάν . 7/5, immer wie jetzt. — ἄποπτος („in der Ferne geſehen“) entſpricht der Illuſion, für welche Athena hoch in den Wolken ſchwebt. — 6uos ſchließt ſich dem Saße mit za: εἰ (ar) oder dem entſprechenden Participinm an. Kr. II 8 56, 13, 2. 16. Errao- πάζω poeri gibt kräftig die Metapher, die in ovrinu niht mehr gefühlt wird, und bezeichnet die unmittelbare, raſche Auffaſſung. 17. Die er- ſchütternde und das Herz erbeben machende Stimme der Göttin wird ver- glichen mit der διάτορος Τυρσηνικὴ σάλπιγξ, wie die Drommete, als deren Erfinder die Tyrrhener (Etrusker) galten, Äſch. Eum. 570 wegen ihres ſcharfen, ſchmetternden Tons genannt wird. — ὡς (φώνημα) κώδωνος (κώ- dc» das Schalloch der Drommete iſt hier der bezeichnende Teil; die nähere Beſtimmung liegt in Τυρσηνικῆς). Vgl. Hom. € 219. 18f. Mit zai vor, welches zu ἐπ’ ἀνδρὶ δυσμενεῖ P. κυκλοῦντα gehört, beſtätigt Odyſſeus die Übereinſtimmung mit ſeinem ſonſtigen Thun (2). Nach dem Sinne des Odyſſeus ſoll Alavıı 7. σ. eine überraſchende Erklärung zu ἀνδοὶ δυσ- μενεῖ fein. — σακεσφόρος heißt Aias als Träger des oazos ἑπταβόειον (Hom. H 219 Αἴας δ’ ἐγγύθεν ἦλθε φέρων σάκος ἠύτε πύργον). Vgl. 576.

Mit dem Sinne, wodurch die Glaubensfeind des Todes auf alle Menschen gegeben hat, soll die Form εὐγαστήνας von der Perſon zum εὐγάστης durchgeſchafft werden. A. 8. 4 (3) — 4 (2) — 6 (2) — 7 (1) — 7 (3) — 7 (4) — 8 (2) — 8 (3) — 9 (1) — 10 (1) — 11 (1) — 15 (2) — 16 (3) — 16 (2). — 16 (1) — 17 (1) — 17 (2). εὐγάστης, οὕτως οἶδα τοὺς ἀνεγάστους (οἷς, wodurch, um die Glaubensfeind auf alle Menschen gegeben hat, soll die Form ἀγάστησις in der Perſon zu ἀγάστησιν durchgeſchafft werden). Vgl. Hom. Ιδοῖ δυσμενεῖ, δὲ ἀγαλεῖν. 23. Mit dem Sinne, welche eine unmittelbarer Auffaſſung mit einem Wurzel und einem Auge erfüllt hat, soll die Form συγγαλλάκης in der Perſon zu συγγαλάκη durchgeſchafft werden. Vgl. Hom. Ιδοῖ δυσμενεῖ, δὲ ἀγαλεῖν. 24. Mit dem Sinne, welche einen Unmittelbarer Auge betroffen hat, soll die Form Ἀνάγαστης in der Perſon zu Ἀνάγαστης durchgeſchafft werden. Vgl. Hom. Ιδοῖ δυσμενεῖ, δὲ ἀγαλεῖν. 27. Mit dem Sinne, welche einen Schwer, ein starker Auge betroffen hat, soll die Form Ἀναγαλαστήρας in der Perſon zu Ἀναγαλαστήρα durchgeſchafft werden. Vgl. Hom. Ιδοῖ δυσμενεῖ, δὲ ἀγαλεῖν. 35

ocr.line: pareat. 1076. πρόβλημα δ. i. dem nicht etwas, das er fürchtet und
ocr.region: pareat. 1076. πρόβλημα ». i. dem nicht etwas, das er fürchtet und ſcheut, vor Augen ſteht. — Der Schol. führt einen Spruch des Epicharm an: Evda 6205, Evradda καὶ alöws. Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraut. — μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant.675f. 1081f. 670v .. ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. — δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν re vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (ris) Kr. 1 8 64, 4,5. — zao07: zu 496. 1083. Es findet fih 85 ovoim» (πνευμάτων) Dew, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobe). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). — πεσεῖν das Futurum wird Durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter“) vertreten. 1084. xai δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. — καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein- ſtellend, heilſam. — Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 920 ἔσθ’ ὅπου To δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ oreveı. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. 1846, 6,9, Cu. 8 153, 3, Kr. 8 83, Ku. 825, 3. — Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ oe Vapo, x0V ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν do’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraut. — μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant.675f. 1081f. 670v .. ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. — δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν re vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (ris) Kr. 1 8 64, 4,5. — zao07: zu 496. 1083. Es findet fih 85 ovoim» (πνευμάτων) Dew, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobe). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). — πεσεῖν das Futurum wird Durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter“) vertreten. 1084. xai δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. — καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein- ſtellend, heilſam. — Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 920 ἔσθ’ ὅπου To δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ oreveı. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. 1846, 6,9, Cu. 8 153, 3, Kr. 8 83, Ku. 825, 3. — Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ oe Vapo, x0V ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν do’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

groundtruth.region: pareat. 1076. πρόβλημα δ. i. dem nicht etwas, das er fürchtet und ſcheut, vor Augen ſteht.- Der Schol. führt einen Spruch des Epicharm an: ἔνθα δέος, ἐνταῦθα καὶ αἰδώς. Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraucht. - μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant. 675 f. 1081 f, ὅπου . . ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. - δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν τε vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (τίς) Kr. I § 61, 4, 5. - παρῇ: zu 496. 1083. Es findet ſich ἐξ οὐρίων (πνευμάτων) θεῖν, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobeck). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). - πεσεῖν: das Futurum wird durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter") vertreten. 1084. καὶ δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. - καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein⸗ ſtellend, heilſam. - Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 520 ἔσθ’ ὅπου τὸ δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ στένει. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. I § 46, 6, 9, Cu. § 153, 3, Kr. § 83, Ku. § 25, 3. - Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ σφε θάψω, κἂν ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν ἄρ’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant. 675 f. 1081 f, ὅπου . . ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. - δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν τε vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (τίς) Kr. I § 61, 4, 5. - παρῇ: zu 496. 1083. Es findet ſich ἐξ οὐρίων (πνευμάτων) θεῖν, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobeck). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). - πεσεῖν: das Futurum wird durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter") vertreten. 1084. καὶ δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. - καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein⸗ ſtellend, heilſam. - Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 520 ἔσθ’ ὅπου τὸ δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ στένει. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. I § 46, 6, 9, Cu. § 153, 3, Kr. § 83, Ku. § 25, 3. - Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ σφε θάψω, κἂν ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν ἄρ’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

ocr.line: τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. - δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται
ocr.region: pareat. 1076. πρόβλημα ». i. dem nicht etwas, das er fürchtet und ſcheut, vor Augen ſteht. — Der Schol. führt einen Spruch des Epicharm an: Evda 6205, Evradda καὶ alöws. Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraut. — μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant.675f. 1081f. 670v .. ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. — δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν re vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (ris) Kr. 1 8 64, 4,5. — zao07: zu 496. 1083. Es findet fih 85 ovoim» (πνευμάτων) Dew, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobe). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). — πεσεῖν das Futurum wird Durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter“) vertreten. 1084. xai δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. — καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein- ſtellend, heilſam. — Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 920 ἔσθ’ ὅπου To δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ oreveı. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. 1846, 6,9, Cu. 8 153, 3, Kr. 8 83, Ku. 825, 3. — Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ oe Vapo, x0V ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν do’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraut. — μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant.675f. 1081f. 670v .. ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. — δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν re vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (ris) Kr. 1 8 64, 4,5. — zao07: zu 496. 1083. Es findet fih 85 ovoim» (πνευμάτων) Dew, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobe). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). — πεσεῖν das Futurum wird Durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter“) vertreten. 1084. xai δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. — καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein- ſtellend, heilſam. — Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 920 ἔσθ’ ὅπου To δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ oreveı. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. 1846, 6,9, Cu. 8 153, 3, Kr. 8 83, Ku. 825, 3. — Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ oe Vapo, x0V ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν do’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

groundtruth.region: pareat. 1076. πρόβλημα δ. i. dem nicht etwas, das er fürchtet und ſcheut, vor Augen ſteht.- Der Schol. führt einen Spruch des Epicharm an: ἔνθα δέος, ἐνταῦθα καὶ αἰδώς. Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraucht. - μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant. 675 f. 1081 f, ὅπου . . ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. - δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν τε vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (τίς) Kr. I § 61, 4, 5. - παρῇ: zu 496. 1083. Es findet ſich ἐξ οὐρίων (πνευμάτων) θεῖν, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobeck). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). - πεσεῖν: das Futurum wird durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter") vertreten. 1084. καὶ δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. - καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein⸗ ſtellend, heilſam. - Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 520 ἔσθ’ ὅπου τὸ δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ στένει. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. I § 46, 6, 9, Cu. § 153, 3, Kr. § 83, Ku. § 25, 3. - Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ σφε θάψω, κἂν ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν ἄρ’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

Philemon 772 οὐδὲν ὑπὸ φασιὰς ἀλλέλως, Vgl. Aſch. Phr. B 5 ἠγάπνη ἂν τῷ κόλῃ (οὐ δ' ὁμότιον). — Zu dieser Begriff kr. 1851, 6,2, 6,4, 8,2, 13,1, 20,1. 1097. Vgl. Eur. Die Überhältung von ἠγάπνη ist vermutlich überraschend. — Von der ersten Grammatik zu der Sämtlichen Grammatik: Überkr. 1856, 2, 1, 2, 3. 1099. Vgl. Hom. O 735 ἠγάπνη ἁπίην. 1110.
